Great idea! Let's split the hosts and run organized scans. Here's a complete solution:

## Step 1: Split the hosts into 8 files

```bash
# Split extips.txt into 8 files
split -n l/8 extips.txt host_set_

# Rename them for clarity
for i in {1..8}; do
    file=$(ls host_set_* | sed -n "${i}p")
    [ -f "$file" ] && mv "$file" "host_set_${i}.txt"
done

# Verify the split
for i in {1..8}; do
    echo "Set $i: $(wc -l < host_set_${i}.txt) hosts"
    echo "---"
    head -3 host_set_${i}.txt
    echo ""
done
```


 
## Step 1: Scan each set manually (one by one)

```bash
# Create a directory for results
mkdir scan_results

# Scan Set 1
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_1 -iL host_set_1.txt

# Scan Set 2
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_2 -iL host_set_2.txt

# Scan Set 3
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_3 -iL host_set_3.txt

# ... and so on for all 8 sets
```

**Or run them all at once in background:**

```bash
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_1 -iL host_set_1.txt &
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_2 -iL host_set_2.txt &
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_3 -iL host_set_3.txt &
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_4 -iL host_set_4.txt &
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_5 -iL host_set_5.txt &
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_6 -iL host_set_6.txt &
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_7 -iL host_set_7.txt &
nmap -sV -sC -O -A --open -p- -T4 -oA scan_results/set_8 -iL host_set_8.txt &
```

## Step 2: After scans complete, manually check each file

```bash
# Go to results directory
cd scan_results

# Look for sensitive stuff in Set 1
grep -i "ftp\|telnet\|smb\|rdp\|mysql\|vnc" set_1.nmap > set_1_sensitive.txt

# Look for sensitive stuff in Set 2
grep -i "ftp\|telnet\|smb\|rdp\|mysql\|vnc" set_2.nmap > set_2_sensitive.txt

# Do the same for all 8 sets
grep -i "ftp\|telnet\|smb\|rdp\|mysql\|vnc" set_3.nmap > set_3_sensitive.txt
grep -i "ftp\|telnet\|smb\|rdp\|mysql\|vnc" set_4.nmap > set_4_sensitive.txt
grep -i "ftp\|telnet\|smb\|rdp\|mysql\|vnc" set_5.nmap > set_5_sensitive.txt
grep -i "ftp\|telnet\|smb\|rdp\|mysql\|vnc" set_6.nmap > set_6_sensitive.txt
grep -i "ftp\|telnet\|smb\|rdp\|mysql\|vnc" set_7.nmap > set_7_sensitive.txt
grep -i "ftp\|telnet\|smb\|rdp\|mysql\|vnc" set_8.nmap > set_8_sensitive.txt
```

## Step 3: Combine all sensitive findings

```bash
# Combine all sensitive findings into one file
cat set_*_sensitive.txt > all_sensitive_findings.txt

# View it
less all_sensitive_findings.txt
```

## Step 4: Manual review checklist

Open each `set_X_sensitive.txt` file and look for:

**ðŸ”´ Critical (Fix immediately):**
- `21/tcp` - FTP (especially if anonymous login)
- `23/tcp` - Telnet (unencrypted)
- `445/tcp` - SMB (check for SMBv1)
- `3389/tcp` - RDP (remote desktop exposed)

**ðŸŸ¡ High Priority:**
- `3306/tcp` - MySQL database
- `5432/tcp` - PostgreSQL database
- `1433/tcp` - MS SQL database
- `5900/tcp` - VNC

**ðŸŸ¢ Review:**
- `22/tcp` - SSH (check version)
- `80/tcp`, `443/tcp` - Web servers
- `8080/tcp`, `8443/tcp` - Web admin panels

## Quick commands to find specific things:

```bash
# Find all FTP servers
grep "21/tcp" scan_results/*.nmap

# Find all Telnet servers
grep "23/tcp" scan_results/*.nmap

# Find all SMB/Windows shares
grep "445/tcp" scan_results/*.nmap

# Find all databases
grep -E "3306|5432|1433|27017" scan_results/*.nmap

# Find all RDP servers
grep "3389/tcp" scan_results/*.nmap
```

